node.text:
HEAR YE HEAR YE! I’m working w/ a company called @infiniteobjects to promote three of @erik.winkowski’s thought-provoking & beautiful video collage art. Infinite Objects has captured Erik’s works inside limited edition, signed & numbered permanently treated displays which contain an endless loop of Erik’s absolutely hypnotic moving collages. There are no buttons & no downloads. You literally lift the display out of the box & the static image comes to life as a piece of collectible video art. It’s a completely amazing & revolutionary way to rethink works & collections of art. I’ll be putting more detail about Erik, Infinite Objects & the inspo for these works of art in my stories, so head over in a bit to see the other limited editions Infinite Objects is offering. This is so much fun. Enjoy!
💙
💙
💙
(Additional art shown by Vic Lee & @pennyfeathersstudio)

node.text:
Final leg of the home tour! Here we have reality check footage of our upstairs bathroom, the original maid’s room & the unfinished attic space. Our plan is to reno the bathroom this winter & we currently have wild & crazy ideas in regard to that space. After the bathroom, the next big project will be converting the very cool & vast attic space into a no holds barred master bedroom suite. The tour finishes off w/ a meander down the original maid’s staircase & back into the kitchen. Keep your eyes peeled later this month or early December for the IGTV tour of our holiday décor. In the meantime, enjoy!

node.text: Part 3 of the video tour of our 1902 Victorian includes the kitchen, original butler’s service pantry, powder room & the old “maid’s staircase” which is a back staircase leading from the kitchen to the back hall on the 2nd floor. If you want to see progress pics showing the full DIY reno (which took almost 2 yrs to complete) you can find them in the gallery on my website @ www.thebeigeblues as well as numerous other “before & after” pics of the rest of the house. One additional snippet of interest that I didn’t cover in the video is that the light blue & glass back door leading to the dilapidated rear deck will be removed when we build a four-season room addition on the back of the house. That will be part of a repair to the exterior brick façade which has been severely damaged due to a prior owner anchoring an upper deck assembly into the veneer rather than the structural brick. In any event, because the four-season room will be directly off the kitchen, we’ll use it as the dining room once it’s complete which hopefully will be before we die. In the meantime, enjoy! And let me know any questions about materials, sources, process etc. & I shall happily answer them. 🧡🧡🧡

node.text: TWO TOPICS starting w/ my Sunday story about the LOL antics of Norman & Donna, an 84 & 82-yr-old who are DIY reno-ing an 1884 🏡 tucked in the 🌳s. Someone asked why HGTV/ 📺 moguls don’t pick up on these kinds of stories & I’ve the same question. Let’s face it – we all get old if we don’t die first = OLD AGE IS A BLESSING. Why not celebrate people taking on big projects at 80 or even 60 (like my husband 😂 – trust me, he doesn’t want to be on 📺)? Diane Lane’s character in Under the Tuscan Sun nailed it when she said, “Unthinkably good things can happen, even late in the game.” Hope really does spring eternal. 🙌🏻 Next topic. IG is taking on TikTok & will aggressively prioritize vids over pics whether we like it or not. Let me just say w/ a 📢 what many think – most interior videos are AWFUL (mine included). W/ exceptions of course, even the best ones aren’t great. Most of us need to improve, & truth usually is the best starting point. The interiors genre just isn’t well suited to video, except reno & progress vids IF (big if) they’re done well. But what to do when the house is done? I popped over to TikTok this morning & saw a popular house acct that must’ve hit a stall on the reno do a “clean the banister” video. Lots of views. Seriously? I don’t even like to clean my own banister. That said, I like change. It’s how our house stays weird. So, I’m willing to improve my vid & editing skills. Maybe. But 1st, should I even try? Do I flex w/ the platform & segue at least in part to video or stay static? 2nd & this is a legit issue I’m having, what are the best user-friendly video apps that are quality BUT won’t end in me throwing all devices + the PC +  desk & everything on it out the window when I reach ZENITH OF FRUSTRATION? 🖥📱▶️🪟🤷🏼‍♀️

node.text: IT’S WORLD CUCUMBER DAY FOR CRYING OUT LOUD! 🥒🥳 In celebration thereof, I’m partnering w/ the wonderfully whimsical HENDRICK’S GIN (@hendricksginus) to bring you this spectacle of botanical bathtub floaties 🌹🥒 topped w/ 1 fabulous Elderflower Gin Gimlet garnished w/ a candied cucumber dipped in GOLD. That’s right! I can think of no better way to glorify the world’s most glamorous gourd than basting it in 2 cups of sugar & rolling it in edible gold. 🤩 Expect nothing less in this house. 🤷🏼‍♀‍ For those not familiar w/ HENDRICK’S GIN, it’s a small-batch gin launched in 1999 & is distilled in 2 rare copper stills via a very elegant process (in Scotland, no less 🏴). Still no. 1 (built in 1860 😲) steeps roses + cucumbers + 11 other botanicals overnight to produce a rich elixir, whilst still no. 2 (built in 1948) delicately steams the botanicals in an overhead basket. The amalgam is a delightfully peculiar, characterful gin which I think smells like perfume (I’m a perfume-forward judger of spirits, if that makes any sense). And I love the candied cucumber as garnish b/c its intense sweetness is an interesting foil to the tart lime juice in the gimlet. Plus gold. GOLD IS MANDATORY. Anyhoo, this is the 1st of 4 posts I’m doing for @hendricksginus between now & the holidays, & to kick this off, do join the fun by sharing in comments your most extraordinary gin cocktail(s) recipes. That’s all for today! In the meantime, swipe for close-ups + relevant recipes & Please Drink the Unusual Responsibly. ✌🏻🥒🌹 #HendricksSociety #Sponsored

node.text: Welcome to our entry hall! This ceiling is the first thing people 👀 after stepping through our tiny vestibule. (I like saying vestibule b/c it sounds like ALL SORTS OF FANCY but in reality, it’s only a closet-sized room w/ an interior door that protects the rest of the house from freezing arctic blasts.) It took just a few touches to take this hall from blah to ooooh & ah & that included (a) a darker, richer blue in a flat sheen 💙, (b) butterflies 🦋 & (c) gilded plaster cracks 💫. Last month w/ SUPREME VENGEANCE I began a synchronized attack on ALL PLASTER CRACKS in our house with metal leaf, because why shouldn’t imperfection be celebrated w/ at least equal supreme vengeance? The concept is a personalized spin-off from the beautiful & meticulous Japanese art known as Kintsugi (aka “golden repair”) whereby broken pottery & china are put back together again w/ lacquer that’s been dusted w/ silver, gold or platinum. The underlying philosophy of Kintsugi is that breakage shouldn’t be hidden in shame, but instead honored as a part of an object’s unique history. I believe the same is true for old houses, hence my refusal hereto forth to patch the friggen walls w/ anything but GOLD. 🤩 Viva la celebración. 🥳 Oh & I think the same should be true for people. On my bucket list are pretty tattoos across my mastectomy scars. That is all. In the meantime, swipe for a few pics of some of our gilded cracks & happy Wednesday! 🎉

node.text: YAHTZEE! I finally figured something out which probably I’ve known subconsciously for a while but it only came to the top of my mind this morning & it’s this: PUSH THAT ENVELOPE UNTIL YOU THINK IT’S TOO FAR. Seriously, it’s no secret I’ve repainted & redecorated rooms in this house 2 & 3 (errrr 4 😂) times before I was reasonably happy with them. The only rooms which have escaped THE WRATH OF THE REDO are the kitchen & upstairs bathroom. I knew with these rooms I had ONE SHOT b/c of the expense of planning large-scale remodels, so I pulled all the stops & pushed things creatively to the point that even I cringed & flinched. And guess what? Wincing seems to be the tipping point for what ultimately will make me happy. If I don’t cringe on Day 1, a redo is just around the corner. By Day 10, I won’t be cringing anymore. I’ll just be happy. Hopefully that’s true with this wall b/c we’re still in the 10-day window & I’m still cringing. Anyone else suffer from The Cringe Threshold in their creative process?🤷🏼‍♀️ It’s a mystery & I shan’t be solving it soon. And btw, I decided against the funky floral DIY collage art on this wall b/c it’s next to a closet & I could see us knocking all or parts of it down every time we opened the door. So, we’ve hung a special piece of art which Mike & I bought for $56 at an antique mall & found out years later is a very rare Rembrandt lifetime etching from the 1630’s. That’s right! These things really do happen. I’ll put a link in my stories later to the blog post I wrote about this adventure & about this extraordinary but humble work of art. That’s all for today. node.text: IT’S FRIDAY’S FEATURE PRESENTATION & PREPARE TO BE INSPIRED b/c we’re headed to a gorgeous rehabbed 1905 firehouse loft in 🍊NJ to visit the massively talented decorative & furniture artist & intuitively gifted designer, Bailey Li of @interiorista_baileyli. Bailey found her way into the design 🌎 after working in corporate sales & as a real estate agent when she began staging properties to help clients visualize blank slates as their own homes. Bailey shies from defining her style b/c she believes it’s always expanding & evolving, although in looking at the sum total of her work, I’d say there’s a thread of dynamically glamorous & romantically gritty energy running through all her projects, including her home which you’ll see in the 1st 4 pics (📸 by @brianwinstonfraser). Of course, the stars of the shows in Bailey’s projects & what takes her work from mere design to actual art installations are her stunning art walls & decorative flourishes she applies to basically any surface w/ lovely mixtures of metallics & color combos ranging from subtle & sublime to spectacularly big & bright alchemies such as the majestic & eyepopping 18-ft mural in pic 5 (this jaw dropper was Bailey’s 1st art wall done for a client). I ❤️ many things about Bailey’s work but, putting aside her obvious technical skill, what impresses me most about this lady is her ability to translate psychology & emotion into aesthetics as she digs deep into her clients’ psyches & uncovers 🔑 elements of their personalities which she then translates into a new physical reality that they can call home (she believes happiness comes from the synergy between environments & their inmates & accomplishes this by ensuring everything surrounding her clients resonates w/ them, so of course each space is intensely personal to its owner & yet they’re so clearly Bailey’s work). I chose Bailey’s own home (the firehouse loft) as the lead pic b/c I’m forever intrigued by how gifted artists & designers assemble & style their personal spaces, but swipe through for a few of her lush projects in pics 5-9. She’s just pure genius. That is all. ❤️

GOING BACK TO THE STORY of why I selected this particular artisan rug as part of my collaboration w/ the exceptional online vintage rug shop @revival, let me start by saying color is EVERYTHING in this house. BUT the process made me realize, in textiles, pattern makes color more relevant & nuanced than I previously appreciated (other than my go-to monochrome checks 🤷🏼‍♀️).  I started the (very fun) process on @revival’s website by focusing just on color & ensuring the rug would fit w/ our plans for the new wall color (which will be a deep, powerful blue) & also the size of the space (the rug needed to be around 6’ 9”). But as I was perusing options, I noticed Revival had certain rugs tagged w/ a button that said “Revival Pick.” Being NEWBIE to the vintage rug market, I decided to narrow my search to these rugs which, per Revival’s description, are the rarest & have the biggest “wow” factor in terms of color, design, technique or material as deemed by their expert team (newbies benefit from expert opinion). This was a whole new experience for me, as it took me outside my comfort zone & provided a new take on how I might present this space. After uploading my photo & plugging in several choices, I ordered “Seppi” mostly b/c of the interesting medallion pattern, the rug’s heritage &, of course, color. Delivery was perfect & the rug surprised me in that it was more intriguing and refined than the photos. The impact of this rug on the space is significant, as the entry hall now feels mysterious & romantic & conveys wisps of Victorian nostalgia, all of which is a perfect introduction to our whimsical home (plus I’m now inspired to turn this corner into a reading nook w/ rich, deep reds & animal print). Head to stories for more info about rug & a link to Revival’s website w/ my discount code (THEBEIGEBLUES10).

node.text: IT’S FRIDAY’S FEATURE PRESENTATION, TUESDAY EDITION & IG doesn’t allow enough words in a caption for me to tell the story of this amazing human + gifted maker of 🧚‍♀️ sculptures + animals on oil + tiny doll house delights = artist @triciasaroya. Tricia had a most eccentric upbringing on a date farm in CA’s Coachella Valley as her free-spirited parents took her out of school in 6th grade & introduced her to the family 📚. Fortunately, pops was a pilot w/ free airline passes so Tricia traveled the world & got an education the fun way before, at 17, going back to school & getting her BA in Art History. She then launched a biz selling southwestern Native American jewelry which lasted almost 10 yrs before she reinvented herself as a merchandiser, which led to a floral design biz, which led to a flourishing even design biz & restoration of an old Santa Barbara area ranch which became 1 of the top 💒 venues in the US. Then life happened & Tricia turned inward. She’d been seeking guidance from her Spirit & asked for a sign (in neon plz) re: next step which happened when she stumbled on a derelict trailer tucked against an old barn. It was riddled w/ holes + mice + rot + unspeakable stains = destined for the dump. NO DUMP FOR YOU! She rescued the sad trailer & friends let her park the rambling wreck on their rural coastal avocado orchard in exchange for Tricia’s work on the infrastructure. A plan was afoot! Tricia dug trenches for pipes, repaired holes & did plumbing + electrical stuff & laid tile. She painted over fugly fake wood, brought in her beloved tea cabinet from India, a fav comfy chair & threw down beautiful thrift-found Oriental rugs. She built a pretty desk, a window seat in lieu of the horrid bolt-down sofa & made sure everything doubled as a storage opportunity. The wee vardo you see in the pic above lives next to the colorful trailer & serves as a fantasy escape pod for meditation & being present in a miraculous life that’s brought Tricia tears, laughter, struggle & love. On the horizon for this creative dynamo (who is a reg contributor to Enchanted Living Mag) is a divination card biz & finishing her book. I shall be 1st in line for that. 🧚‍♀️

BEHOLD OUR NEW ENTRY HALL RUG which I received from @revival as part of a collaboration w/ this purveyor of gorgeous vintage & handmade rugs. Most things in our home have a backstory & this rug is no exception as it speaks aloud my new passion for ALL THINGS WABI-SABI, i.e. vintage & handmade textiles/art that celebrate the PERFECT BEAUTY OF IMPERFECTION in all its arty iterations. Until 6ish months ago all the rugs in our house were of the mass-produced varietal, but I started feeling a tug to add vintage/one-off into the mix. The end result was the vintage red rug in our den which Mike & I agreed changed the entire personality of the space for the better. AND THUS began my crusade for something more characterful to replace the b&w checked rug in our entry hall. The process was tedious & harrowing b/c it involved many hours of cross-eyed sorting & saving & screenshots of 47,387 (😂 🤷🏼‍♀️) rugs on Internet marketplaces, many of which were of dubious origin & quality b/c when it comes to most online vintage rugs, BUYER BEWARE. But then KISMET OCCURRED, b/c Revival emailed me in the midst of my search & asked if I’d like to collaborate & select a rug from their collection. Before responding, I 👀’d at Revival’s website & went down the rabbit hole of a highly curated assemblage of one-of-a-kind, handmade rugs. I was interested in the company’s origin, which is based on direct relationships w/ artisans & partners in Turkey who help Revival bring premium handmade rugs directly to the consumer (which, significantly, makes the rugs affordable as there’s no middle seller marking things up). I also was impressed that each rug came w/ curator’s notes about provenance & physical details of each piece which to me = integrity & reliability (each rug has its own name, btw). So …. I said yes to the collab! But to learn why I said yes to THIS rug, stay tuned. In the meantime, head to stories later today for details & a link for my discount code (THEBEIGEBLUES10).

node.text: IT’S FRIDAY’S FEATURE PRESENTATION – WEDNESDAY EDITION & PUT YOUR 👀 BACK IN YOUR HEAD b/c we’re coming in hot w/ the 🤩🖤 dark & gilded gothic glam acct aka @raspberry_flavoured_windows headed by Devonshire-based Rachel, an uber creative designer, blogger & DIYer who lives w/ the hubs + 3 sons + doggo Buster in a dramatic historic beauty built in 1894. Rachel knew from the first moment she stepped over the threshold 24 yrs ago, this would be her forever home (even though it was a fixer upper in need of HUGE TLC). Fortunately, Rachel is an old house (& old car) aficionado & had the ingenuity & gritty tenacity to DIY her home into a state of alluring magnificence, and impressively did most of the work herself & on a tight budget. In a prior life, Rachel was a designer specializing in paint effects before segueing into furniture design. She & the hubs then grew that into a thriving biz before it ended in 2017, although some of her designs remain displayed in the bedroom and dining room. Nowadays, Rachel is a full-time carer for 2 of her sons, both of whom are diagnosed w/ autism. Being RENAISSANCE WOMAN, Rachel’s spun her know-how into an eclectic, gorgeous & very inspiring blog that covers topics ranging from design & homemaking to DIYing on a budget & autism awareness. Rachel’s allergic to trends & she believes homes should increase a sense of well-being (especially these days) & reflect the varied personalities of its inmates. Of course, this is something she’s pulled off brilliantly in her own home which she designed from a sensory perspective to induce calm & reduce anxiety for her sons. Her inspo comes from classical design, the surrounding world, historic Italian architecture & its decadent interiors. Oh, & she LOVES gold leaf, interesting focal points that spur engaging conversation, & of course interiors that pack a surprise. Lastly, Rachel was nominated for the Mineheart Interior Design Awards & her ❤️ would sing if she was shortlisted, so plz 🙏🏻 head to her profile for the link then scroll down to the “Sensory Home Design” project & give it ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ & a kind word or 2. Few deserve this as much as Rachel. 🖤

node.text: IT’S FRIDAY’S FEATURE PRESENTATION – TUESDAY EDITION 🥳 & SO MUCH JOYOUSNESS IS IN STORE as we’re off to London 💃🏼 to visit Sarah of the gracefully laid back & maximal @ahometomakeyousmile. And it’s 2-FOR-1 SPECIAL b/c Sarah’s acct features 2 unique homes, one being a light-filled & cheery 1908 Arts & Crafts & the other a VERY OLD seaside rustic chic fisherman’s cottage where she abides w/ hubs Guy, 2 teens + 2 sweet spaniels which are STARS OF THE SHOW. Sarah’s story starts years ago w/ a gig working for an ad agency in Paddington where she met Guy & basked in the glow of creativity for many years before shifting gears, retraining & working as a primary school teacher in SE London. During this time, Sarah & Gary took many travel jaunts to SE Asia & even jumped into the deep end (literally) &, never having sailed before, somehow ended up on a mad cap adventure racing in the VERY HAIRBRAINED & SCARY Coral Sea Classic Yacht Race from Cairns to Port Moresby in Papua New Guinea. Probably they’re lucky to be alive. Next, the couple moved to Singapore where Sarah worked in int’l schools, taught creative writing @ local schools & worked for a women’s rights charity. The dynamic duo then moved back to the UK & embarked on responsible things like kids & house renos, during which time Sarah subsumed herself in EPIC HEROIC STRUGGLE, i.e., finding her interiors style which THANK THE LORD she found thanks to Abigail Ahern’s Ostrich Table & Downpipe walls. LONG LIVE ALL MOODY THINGS W/ BIRD FEET! Sarah then got sucked into the interiors 🌎 from which she’s never emerged & began taking courses & teaching herself the trade. She’s influenced most by traditional designers & old-fashioned houses filled w/ 🌈 + 📚 + 💐 + 🐶🐶 + timeworn patina + & rugs & people & THERE’S JUST SO MUCH TO LOVE! Sarah now helps friends & locals find their style & gussy up their houses. Her interiors ethos is that decorating should be done slowly whilst understanding a home’s heritage & features & building on them. But most of all, she says a home should make you smile. 😊 Amen to that Sarah.

node.text: GREETINGS FROM THE FROZEN TUNDRA! 🙋🏼‍♀️ It’s been forever & a fruitcake since I last posted & thus SO MANY THINGS TO REPORT. Fortunately, none are important. The reno presses on & the current agenda includes attic electrical before more framing & then next week COMMENCEMENT OF THE DORMER. So excited. More trusses for the back room are arriving as I write this. Our backyard looks like the mud pit at a greased pig contest & the front yard isn’t much better. There’s a giant scissor lift in the parkway next to a huge dumpster overflowing w/ parts of our house & whatever else the neighbors didn’t have room for in their own trash. Probably there’s a couch in there. The guest room is stacked to the ceiling w/ debris interspersed w/ residual Christmas & somewhere around here there’s a dog in need of a dental. Other than that, IT’S ALL GOOD. I have, in fact, been working on my book. I laugh as I write this b/c so far my process has been riddled w/ more resistance than you can possibly imagine. I was an English major & a lawyer for a couple decades so I’ve written enough pages in my life to fill a nice section in the Library of Congress but my brain works differently when engaged in the deductive processes involved in analytical writing as opposed to the inductive processes required for creative writing. I could write an analytical book about design & it’d be done in a week but no one would read it. In fact, my process has been so circuitous that I finally stepped away from the keyboard when I found myself researching new romanticism in contemporary art & the Greco-Roman origins of the genius myth. I even bought books on both subjects. Read them all. One more on order. THE STRUGGLE IS REAL. I don’t have anything else to report. One day the book will be done. Goodbye. 👋🏻
